\begin_layout Section
Data Model and Related Work
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The design of a query language is closely guided by its choice of data model.
 While we defer a formal treatment of Prela's data model to Section TODO,
 this Section provides a high-level discussion in the context of several related design points.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
As Prela is built upon the formal foundation of Tarski's Relational Algebra where the fundamental data type is the 
\emph on
binary
\emph default
 relation,
 our data model can be understood as an instantiation of the Entity/Relational model.
 Consider again the query 29a,
 which can be understood as operating over 
\begin_inset listings
inline true
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
movie
\end_layout

\end_inset

 entities (of entity 
\lang english
type 
\begin_inset listings
inline true
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Movie
\end_layout

\end_inset

),
 while we use the 
\begin_inset listings
inline true
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
.
\end_layout

\end_inset

 syntax to access various attributes of the entity.
 In our experience this is a helpful mental model when programming in Prela.
 This syntax also connects Prela to object-oriented and document data,
 for which SQL infamously struggles to model due to impedance mismatch.
 Users of document/nested query languages like XPath or the more recent jq may find Prela's syntax familiar.
 This is not a coincidence,
 as Tarski's Relational Algebra has also been used to analyze nested data models.
 Unlike these langauges,
 Prela is not constrained to a single nested data schema or to the nested data model.
 In our example query,
 
\begin_inset listings
inline true
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
cast
\end_layout

\end_inset

 appears to be a nested attribute under 
\begin_inset listings
inline true
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
movie
\end_layout

\end_inset

,
 but the programmer is free to define a 
\begin_inset listings
inline true
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
stars_in
\end_layout

\end_inset

 relation over 
\begin_inset listings
inline true
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Cast
\end_layout

\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset listings
inline true
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Movie
\end_layout

\end_inset

 then query 
\begin_inset listings
inline true
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
cast.stars_in
\end_layout

\end_inset

.
 This is because 
\begin_inset listings
inline true
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
.
\end_layout

\end_inset

 is in fact the 
\emph on
relational composition operator
\emph default
 (defined in TODO) under the hood,
 and requires no syntactic extension to the host language to implement.
 Tarski's Relational Algebra has also been applied to formalize various graph query languages TODO CITE,
 where binary relation naturally model edge sets.
 While graph query languages aim to support a wide range of multi-hop,
 recursive queries over large networks,
 the current focus of Prela is non-recursive queries over tabular data.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Last but not least,
 the original motivation of Prela was to address issues in practical instantiations of Codd's relational model.
 At SQL's 50th anniversary,
 the language co-creator Don Chamerlin questioned two design decisions:
 the need for nulls to represent missing data,
 and the allowance of duplicated data (
\emph on
a la
\emph default
 bag semantics).
 In the programming languages community,
 nulls were considered a 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

billion-dollar mistake
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 by its creator Tony Hoare,
 and many modern languages have adopted features like option types to rid of nulls.
 Yet,
 nulls prevail in every SQL database today.
 Similarly,
 bag semantics was offered as a convinience for database users and system builders,
 yet continues to frustrate both groups.
 To remove the reliance on nulls and bag semantics,
 Prela follows the approach of the Rel programming language and operate over fully normalized data:
 a wide relation over many columns is 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

shredded
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 into multiple 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

skinny
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 relations,
 each over two columns,
 a primary key column (think 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

row number
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 of the original table) and data column.
 For example,
 the 
\begin_inset listings
inline true
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
movie
\end_layout

\end_inset

 table (originally named 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

title
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

) from JOB over attributes 
\begin_inset listings
inline true
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
id
\end_layout

\end_inset

,
 
\begin_inset listings
inline true
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
title
\end_layout

\end_inset

,
 
\begin_inset listings
inline true
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
production_year
\end_layout

\end_inset

,
 ...
 ,
 is represented with a 
\begin_inset listings
inline true
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
title
\end_layout

\end_inset

 table mapping each 
\begin_inset listings
inline true
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
id
\end_layout

\end_inset

 to the title text,
 a 
\begin_inset listings
inline true
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
production_year
\end_layout

\end_inset

 table mapping each 
\begin_inset listings
inline true
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
id
\end_layout

\end_inset

 to the production year,
 etc.,
 one per non-primary key attribute of the original table.
 In each shredded relation,
 the primary key constraint on the first column rules out the possibility of duplicates,
 and a missing value is naturally represented by the absence of an entry in the corresponding 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

shred
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

.
 There is theoretical evidence that giving up nulls does not compromise expressiveness,
 and the normalization approach has proven to be practical by large scale deployments of Rel.
 The key distinction between Prela and Rel goes back to the algebraic foundation of Prela – while Rel is a declarative language based on Datalog,
 Prela is imperative and therefore 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

closer to the metal
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

,
 while remaining readable as demonstrated by the examples.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
The Prela Language
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This Section defines the data model,
 syntax,
 and semantics of the Prela query language.
 While Prela is based on a mathematical formalization of relations due to Tarski,
 we feel a rote recitation of the formalism would overwhelm the reader and detract from the simple essence of Prela.
 Instead,
 we will introduce language constructs one-by-one,
 guided by examples,
 without attempting to fully cover the formal algebra.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Data Model.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The fundamental datatype of Prela is (typed) relations of no more than two columns.
 Although retricting relations to be at most binary may appear limiting at first glance,
 it is simple to recover the flexibility of multi-column tables with ones over only two columns.
 We have demonstrated this in Section TODO with the 
\begin_inset listings
inline true
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
movie
\end_layout

\end_inset

 table which is 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

shredded
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 into multiple two-column tables,
 each mapping the row to the value under the corresponding column.
 Perhaps a better starting point to understand Prela's data model is the Entity/Relationship model:
 entities of type 
\begin_inset listings
inline true
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Movie
\end_layout

\end_inset

 can be represented as a unary relation (over the 
\begin_inset listings
inline true
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
id
\end_layout

\end_inset

s),
 and a relation 
\begin_inset listings
inline true
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
title
\end_layout

\end_inset

 over column types 
\begin_inset listings
inline true
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Movie
\end_layout

\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset listings
inline true
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
String
\end_layout

\end_inset

 maps each movie to its title text.
 We will intuitively write the type of the 
\begin_inset listings
inline true
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
title
\end_layout

\end_inset

 table as 
\begin_inset listings
inline true
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Movie -> String
\end_layout

\end_inset

.
 While the 
\begin_inset listings
inline true
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
title
\end_layout

\end_inset

 relation represents an attribute of the 
\begin_inset listings
inline true
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Movie
\end_layout

\end_inset

 entity,
 we can also model relationships between entities:
 the 
\begin_inset listings
inline true
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
stars_in
\end_layout

\end_inset

 relation introduced in Section TODO has type 
\begin_inset listings
inline true
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Cast -> Movie
\end_layout

\end_inset

 and tells us which actor stars in which movie.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Relational Combinators.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Prela queries are composed of operators applied to relational arguments,
 much like the classic Relational Algebra 
\emph on
a la 
\emph default
Codd.
 We will refer to Prela's operators as 
\emph on
combinators
\emph default
 to emphasize on their purely algebraic nature.
 The most powerful combinator is the relational composition 
\begin_inset listings
inline true
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
.
\end_layout

\end_inset

 which takes two binary relations,
 joins them,
 and produces a binary relation.
 Formally (writing 
\begin_inset Formula $\circ$
\end_inset

 for 
\begin_inset listings
inline true
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
.
\end_layout

\end_inset

):
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Definition
The composition 
\begin_inset Formula $R\circ S$
\end_inset

 over relations 
\begin_inset Formula $R:X\to Y$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $S:Y\to Z$
\end_inset

 is the relation 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ (x,z)\mid\exists y.(x,y)\in R\land(y,z)\in S\right\} $
\end_inset

 of type 
\begin_inset Formula $X\to Z$
\end_inset

.
 When one or both of the arguments are unary,
 composition is defined in the natural way TODO put in footnote?:
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
If 
\begin_inset Formula $R:Y$
\end_inset

,
 
\begin_inset Formula $S:Y\to Z$
\end_inset

,
 
\begin_inset Formula $R\circ S=\left\{ (y,z)\mid y\in R\land(y,z)\in S\right\} $
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
If 
\begin_inset Formula $R:X\to Y$
\end_inset

,
 
\begin_inset Formula $S:Y$
\end_inset

,
 
\begin_inset Formula $R\circ S=\left\{ (x,y)\mid(x,y)\in R\land y\in S\right\} $
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
If 
\begin_inset Formula $R:X$
\end_inset

,
 
\begin_inset Formula $S:X$
\end_inset

,
 
\begin_inset Formula $R\circ S=\left\{ x\mid x\in R\land x\in S\right\} $
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Or in positional relational algebra:
 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi_{(R.1,S.2)}(R\bowtie_{R.2=S.1}S)$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $R.i$
\end_inset

 indicates the 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

-th column of 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

.
 The corresponding SQL query is 
\begin_inset listings
inline true
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
SELECT distinct(R.x,
 S.z) FROM R,
 S WHERE R.y = S.y
\end_layout

\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Example
Given unary relation 
\begin_inset listings
inline true
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
movie
\end_layout

\end_inset

 of type 
\begin_inset listings
inline true
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Movie
\end_layout

\end_inset

 and binary relation 
\begin_inset listings
inline true
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
title
\end_layout

\end_inset

 of type 
\begin_inset listings
inline true
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Movie -> String
\end_layout

\end_inset

 ,
 their composition 
\begin_inset listings
inline true
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
movie.title
\end_layout

\end_inset

 is a binary relation of type 
\begin_inset listings
inline true
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Movie -> String
\end_layout

\end_inset

.
 Specifically,
 it is the subset of the 
\begin_inset listings
inline true
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
title
\end_layout

\end_inset

 relation such that the first attribute appears in the 
\begin_inset listings
inline true
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
movie
\end_layout

\end_inset

 relation.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Composition is powerful because it allows us to 
\emph on
zoom in
\emph default
 by composing multiple relations:
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Example
The query 
\begin_inset listings
inline true
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
movie.cast.person.name
\end_layout

\end_inset

 lists,
 for each movie,
 the names of all actors starring in that movie.
 It is a 3-step composition:
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
\begin_inset listings
inline true
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
movie.cast
\end_layout

\end_inset

 has type 
\begin_inset listings
inline true
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Movie -> Cast
\end_layout

\end_inset

 and lists the casting table for each movie;
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
\begin_inset listings
inline true
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
movie.cast.person
\end_layout

\end_inset

 has type 
\begin_inset listings
inline true
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Movie -> Person
\end_layout

\end_inset

 and lists all 
\begin_inset listings
inline true
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Person
\end_layout

\end_inset

 entities in the cast;
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Finally,
 
\begin_inset listings
inline true
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
movie.cast.person.name
\end_layout

\end_inset

 composes the relation from the last step with 
\begin_inset listings
inline true
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
name
\end_layout

\end_inset

 to list the names.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Intuitively,
 relational composition can be thought of as a join and a projection,
 or,
 as the name suggests,
 a generalization of function composition.
 It can also been seen as multiplying boolean matrices.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Next,
 filtering in Prela is expressed by directly applying the predicate to a relation:
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Definition
Given predicate 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi$
\end_inset

 and binary relation 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

,
 the expression 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi(R)$
\end_inset

 is the relation 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ (x,y)\in R\mid\phi(y)\right\} $
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Note that predicates can only be applied to the second column of a binary relation,
 because unary relations in Prela can only store opaque entity types.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Filtered relations can be intersected and combined with the familiar boolean connectives 
\begin_inset listings
inline true
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
&
\end_layout

\end_inset

 (formally 
\begin_inset Formula $\land$
\end_inset

) and 
\begin_inset listings
inline true
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
|
\end_layout

\end_inset

 (formally 
\begin_inset Formula $\lor$
\end_inset

),
 as well as the set difference 
\begin_inset listings
inline true
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\backslash

\end_layout

\end_inset

 :
\end_layout

\begin_layout Definition
For relations 
\begin_inset Formula $R:X\to Y,S:X\to Z$
\end_inset

,
 their 
\emph on
intersection
\emph default
 
\begin_inset Formula $R\land S$
\end_inset

 is the unary relation 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ x\mid\exists y.(x,y)\in R\land\exists z.(x,z)\in S\right\} $
\end_inset

;
 their 
\emph on
union
\emph default
 
\begin_inset Formula $R\lor S$
\end_inset

 is the relation 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ x\mid\exists y.(x,y)\in R\lor\exists z.(x,z)\in S\right\} $
\end_inset

;
 their difference is the relation 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ x\mid\exists y.(x,y)\in R\land\exists z.(x,z)\not\in S\right\} $
\end_inset

.
 When an input relation is unary,
 the operators are extended in the natural way.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
With composition,
 predicates,
 and boolean connectives,
 we can specify complex selection queries in Prela in a natural way:
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Example
The query 
\begin_inset listings
inline true
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
movie.(production_year >= 2000 & production_year <= 2010)
\end_layout

\end_inset

 returns all movies made between the years of 2000 and 2010.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The next example shows why boolean connectives operate only on the first column of the input relations:
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Example
The query 
\begin_inset listings
inline true
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
movie.(production_year >= 2000 & company.country = '[us]')
\end_layout

\end_inset

 returns movies produced after 2000 by US-based companies.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Because intersection focuses on the first column of the inputs,
 it allows us to combine prediactes over different data types.
 Also note that,
 in the above query,
 we can freely intermix composition,
 prediactes,
 and intersection,
 because each is simply a relational combinator under the hood.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A couple more combinators are needed to express select-project-join queries.
 First,
 the 
\begin_inset listings
inline true
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
:
\end_layout

\end_inset

 combinator is akin to the 
\begin_inset listings
inline true
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
SELECT
\end_layout

\end_inset

 clause in SQL:
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Definition
For relations 
\begin_inset Formula $R:X$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $S:X\to Y$
\end_inset

 ,
 the expression 
\begin_inset Formula $R:S$
\end_inset

 is the relation 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ (x,y)\in S\mid x\in R\right\} $
\end_inset

.
 When the first input 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 is binary,
 its second column is ignored.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We will also write 
\begin_inset listings
inline true
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
S where R
\end_layout

\end_inset

 as a syntactic sugar for 
\begin_inset listings
inline true
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
R :
 S
\end_layout

\end_inset

,
 i.e.,
 the 
\begin_inset listings
inline true
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
where
\end_layout

\end_inset

 combinator is the same as 
\begin_inset listings
inline true
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
:
\end_layout

\end_inset

 but with the arugments swapped.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Example
The query 
\begin_inset listings
inline true
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
movie.(company.country = '[us]' :
 title)
\end_layout

\end_inset

 returns the titles of all movies made by American companies.
 We can also apply predicates to the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

selected attributes
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

:
 
\begin_inset listings
inline true
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
movie.(title != 'Shrek 2' where company.country = '[us]')
\end_layout

\end_inset

 excercises the 
\begin_inset listings
inline true
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
where
\end_layout

\end_inset

 combinator and will be helpful for those who dislike Shrek.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
As Tarski's Relational Algebra fundamentally restricts relations to be at most binary,
 a particular challenge is to return a result over multiple columns.
 One pedantic solution is to write multiple queries,
 one for each output attribute,
 returning multiple correlated binary relations at the same time that can be joined by the user.
 This is inspired by the recent idea of allowing queries to return a full database instead of a single table TODO CITE.
 However,
 in Prela we choose to implement a more pragmatic approach:
 we allow columns to store record data types.
 Another motivation is that record-typed columns leads to a natural implementation of group-by aggregation which will be covered soon.
 Nevertheless,
 we recognize that having record data betrays the purity of the formal foundation of Tarski's Relational Algebra,
 and time will tell if this design turns out to be a mistake for Prela like that of nulls and duplicates for SQL.
 We also remark that impurity in Prela is 
\emph on
contained
\emph default
 within record creation and aggregations that group by records,
 both of which usually occur as the last step of a query.
 The 
\emph on
product
\emph default
 operator 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset


\begin_inset listings
inline true
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
,
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 (formally 
\begin_inset Formula $\times$
\end_inset

) creates a record from its arguments:
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Definition
For 
\begin_inset Formula $R:X\to Y$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $S:X\to Z$
\end_inset

,
 their 
\emph on
product
\emph default
 
\begin_inset Formula $R\times S$
\end_inset

 is a relation of type 
\begin_inset Formula $X\to\left\{ R:Y,S:Z\right\} $
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ R:Y,S:Z\right\} $
\end_inset

 denotes a record type with field 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 of type 
\begin_inset Formula $Y$
\end_inset

 and field 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

 of type 
\begin_inset Formula $Z$
\end_inset

.
 The content of the relation is 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ (x,\left\{ R:y,S:z\right\} )\mid(x,y)\in R\land(x,z)\in S\right\} $
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Example
The query 
\begin_inset listings
inline true
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
movie.cast.(character,
 person)
\end_layout

\end_inset

 returns what character each actor plays for every movie.
 In other words,
 the 
\begin_inset listings
inline true
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
,
\end_layout

\end_inset

 operator joins 
\begin_inset listings
inline true
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
character:
 Cast -> Character
\end_layout

\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset listings
inline true
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Person:
 Cast -> Person
\end_layout

\end_inset

 to produce a relation of type 
\begin_inset listings
inline true
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Cast -> {character:
 Character,
 person:
 Person}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 which is composed with 
\begin_inset listings
inline true
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
cast
\end_layout

\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset listings
inline true
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
movie
\end_layout

\end_inset

 to list the roles per movie.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Record types pave the way for grouping by multiple attributes for aggregation,
 together with the 
\emph on
inverse
\emph default
 operator 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset


\begin_inset listings
inline true
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
~
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 (formally 
\begin_inset Formula $R^{-1}$
\end_inset

):
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Definition
The 
\emph on
inverse
\emph default
 of a relation 
\begin_inset Formula $R:X\to Y$
\end_inset

 is the relation 
\begin_inset Formula $R^{-1}:Y\to X=\left\{ (y,x)\mid(x,y)\in R\right\} $
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To apply an aggregation,
 we generalize the composition operator 
\begin_inset listings
inline true
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
.
\end_layout

\end_inset

 to accept aggregate functions:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Definition
An aggregate function takes in a set of values and produces a single value.
 For an aggregate function 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma$
\end_inset

 and relation 
\begin_inset Formula $R:X\to Y$
\end_inset

,
 their composition 
\begin_inset Formula $R\circ\gamma$
\end_inset

 is the relation 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ (x,\sum_{y:(x,y)\in R}y)\mid\exists z.(x,z\in R)\right\} $
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In other words,
 
\begin_inset listings
inline true
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
R.f
\end_layout

\end_inset

 groups by the first attribute of 
\begin_inset listings
inline true
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
R
\end_layout

\end_inset

 and aggregates over the second attribute per group using 
\begin_inset listings
inline true
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
f
\end_layout

\end_inset

.
 We are now ready to implement SQL's group-by aggregate using inversion and aggregate functions:
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Example
To find when each company produced its first movie,
 we compose the inverse of the 
\begin_inset listings
inline true
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
company
\end_layout

\end_inset

 relation with the 
\begin_inset listings
inline true
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
production_year
\end_layout

\end_inset

 relation and apply the min-aggregate:
 
\begin_inset listings
inline true
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
(~company.movie.production_year).min
\end_layout

\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To group by multiple attributes,
 we take the inverse of their product:
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Example
The query 
\begin_inset listings
inline true
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
(~(company,cast.person).movie.production_year).min
\end_layout

\end_inset

 finds the first time a production company has collaborated with an actor.
 
\end_layout

